'''Dabarkot''', or '''Dabar Kot''', is a [[Tell (archaeology)|tell]] site of the [[Indus Civilization]] in [[Balochistan, Pakistan]]. The large city was once a trading post dating back to fifth millennium BC. Various artifacts and figurines excavated from the area show a [[Harappa]]n connection of the site.<ref name=dict>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedic Dictionary of Archaeology.|date=2011|publisher=Springer Verlag|isbn=978-1-4419-3322-5|page=146|doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-5133-8_4|chapter=Dd|last1=Kipfer|first1=Barbara Ann}}</ref> The Dabarkot mound is 500 yards in diameter showing the settlement was large in size and of considerable significance.<ref name=bb>{{cite book|last=Bhattacharya|first=B.|title=Urban development in India : since pre-historic times|date=2006|publisher=Concept Pub. Co.|location=New Delhi|isbn=9788180692406|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sdDCdpD3RRMC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=dabarkot#v=onepage&q=dabarkot&f=false|edition=2nd rev.}}</ref> Excavations from the site recovered various artifacts including stone beads, copper pieces, a gold pin, sheet metal, and large mud bricks.<ref name=bb/>
It is believed that after the Indus Civilization, the mound was destroyed and inhabited by other cultures.<ref name=dict/><ref>{{cite book|title=The Civilized Demons: The Harappans in Rigveda|first=Malati J. |last=Shendge|date=2003|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=9788170170648|page=159|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tf-ThAPjqZAC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=dabarkot#v=onepage&q=dabarkot&f=false}}</ref>
The present day site is located in the [[Loralai District]] of Balochistan and is under the [[Government of Pakistan|federal]] protection under the Antiquities Act 1975.
